TI  - 2030 - A waste(d) world?
T2  - PRES '99: 2ND CONFERENCE ON PROCESS INTEGRATION, MODELLING AND OPTIMISATION FOR ENERGY SAVING AND POLLUTION REDUCTION
LA  - English
CP  - 2nd Conference on Process Integration, Modelling and Optimisation for Energy Saving and Pollution Reduction (PRES 99)
AB  - Four images of 2030' waste infrastructure were constructed to determine the scope of a decision support tool for the design and management of waste infrastructure. Public awareness and attitude were identified as the main parameters that determine the future context, apart from technological development, resource scarcity and fnal abatement of waste processing residues. The concept 'waste' was assessed, and redefined as 'an emerged quality of a substance that is qualified as waste when not used to its full potential'. The material cycles concept was adopted as the basis for system modelling to demonstrate the interdependence between the availability and fate of all atomic elements. The rearrangement and closing of material cycles opens the way to eliminate landfill of harmful residues and contributes to the conservation of resources. Material cycle modelling provides a convenient method of abstraction to present the system alternatives to decision-makers. The consideration, appreciation and adoption of less obvious but worthwhile options can he improved by the apt supply of such information.
