KW  - CALIFORNIA
AB  - Managing ecosystems for resilience to climate change requires collaboration, innovation and communication. The abundance of data and documents describing the uncertainty around both climate change projections and impacts has become challenging to managers who have little funding and limited time to digest and incorporate these materials into planning and implementation documents. The Conservation Biology Institute (CBI) is working with resource agencies from federal, state, and local government to provide usable information for a variety of vulnerability assessments. CBI created Data Basin (databasin.org) to centralize valuable spatial data, including state-of-the-art climate and vegetation response projections, and to provide the necessary system functionality to help users work with the data and each other to make more informed decisions. MC1 is prominently featured in Data Basin and many MC1 results are now available through the site. CBI also developed a decision support framework, called the environmental evaluation modeling system (EEMS), that uses climate change information such as MC1 and other simulation results together with observations and socioeconomic constraints to help develop more effective adaptation strategies.
