KW  - Alpine grassland vegetation
KW  - Sustainable harvesting
KW  - SMALL OBJECT DETECTION
KW  - FEATURE FUSION
KW  - BENTH. KUDO
AB  - Monitoring the population dynamics of medicinal plants is vital for sustainable agriculture and biodiversity conservation. However, traditional field surveys are constrained by labor intensity and limited spatial-temporal coverage. This study presents a UAV-based deep learning framework, SAA-YOLO, for spatiotemporal monitoring of Phlomoides rotata (PR), a rare alpine medicinal plant on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau. The proposed model integrates a scale-aware attention (SAA) mechanism into YOLOv10s, combining multi-scale dilated convolution and channel-wise attention for scale-aware feature fusion to enhance small-object detection in complex alpine environments. Multi-temporal UAV imagery from 2020, 2022, and 2024 was used for model training and validation. SAA-YOLO achieved an F1 score of 96.89% and a mAP0.5:0.95 of 80.49%, outperforming baseline and existing attention-enhanced detectors. Independent validation showed strong correlations with ground truth (R2 = 0.970 for abundance, R2 = 0.963 for canopy coverage), confirming high reliability for ecological assessment. Temporal analysis revealed a marked decline in PR populations, with individuals decreasing from 38,596 in 2020 to 25,168 in 2024, alongside a 44.0% reduction in canopy coverage. Although spatial clustering persisted, aggregation intensity weakened over time, indicating increasing vulnerability to environmental stress. Overall, SAA-YOLO demonstrates an effective, scalable solution for long-term monitoring of rare alpine plants. By generating high-resolution spatiotemporal datasets, this framework provides a decision-support tool for sustainable harvesting and conservation management of valuable medicinal resources in fragile alpine ecosystems.
