AB  - India is an agricultural country, with fertile land, a good climate, and low wages. India is expected to compete with rival agricultural superpowers such as the United States and Australia. The value of fresh fruit, vegetables, and flower exports has tripled in recent years. India is the second-largest grower of fruits and vegetables. However, its exports have accounted for only 1 percent of the world's agricultural trade. Inadequate market information, poor infrastructure and insufficient agribusiness finance knowledge have contributed to this problem. With an overwhelming density of population we Indians need to seriously consider the land conservation issue also. This in turn will help us to avail more land for agricultural purpose.
   This paper discusses the impact of Information Technology which will supply information and decision support in agriculture. We suggest the use of WWW, to build collaborative information systems where institutions with different fields of expertise can contribute with modules of information resources, which can be assembled via the WWW at the time of enquiry. The use of IT is essential for farmer upliftment, initiating new applications of agriculture, animal husbandry, GIS in the towns, villages and farming etc.
