TI  - Herbicide-resistant crops in farming systems
T2  - HERBICIDE-RESISTANT CROPS AND PASTURES IN AUSTRALIAN FARMING SYSTEMS
LA  - English
CP  - Workshop on Herbicide-Resistant Crops and Pastures in Australian Farming Systems
AB  - More effective weed control is needed because some weeds cannot be controlled in some crops. There is also a need for a higher standard of weed control to remove weedy hosts of soil-borne pathogens and to support conservation farming. Herbicide-resistant crops offer a cheap and effective way to solve these problems. A possible adverse consequence is herbicide overuse, leading to excess residues in products, environmental pollution and development of more herbicide-resistant weeds. Risks of these hazards could be greatly reduced if farmers are educated to avoid overuse and to adopt integrated weed management. Decision-support systems for herbicide management should be reassessed in the light of the greater complexity of weed control with herbicide-resistant crops and herbicide-resistant weeds.
   Other factors to consider are the control of herbicide-resistant crops themselves, or their relatives if they ''go feral''. This problem could be severe if multiple resistance develops through a combination of two or more herbicide-resistance genes. Selection of a crop as a candidate for herbicide resistance should consider the farming system, industry structure and product markets. Decisions should not be driven by the availability of a suitable gene.
