TI  - Forages at the crossroads - Production and utilization
T2  - 1998 AMERICAN FORAGE AND GRASSLAND COUNCIL, PROCEEDINGS: FORAGES AT THE CROSSROADS
LA  - English
CP  - 1998 Forage and Grassland Conference
KW  - SILAGE
AB  - Animal performance from forage is normally limited by a combination of low voluntary food intake and poor nutritive value, reflected in a low efficiency of energy and protein use. However, current progress in grass breeding and grazing management techniques, coupled with a better understanding of the processes involved in forage conservation offers considerable scope to improve animal production from forage. Given the lower resource inputs and higher nutritive value of grazed relative to conserved forage, maximum reliance on grazing should form the basis of sustainable farming systems in those areas well suited for grass growth. There is a need for greater emphasis on food intake characteristics in plant and animal breeding programmes coupled with ongoing research to develop new grass varieties and/or grazing management techniques which will maintain high quality grass swards throughout the season, even under reduced grazing intensity. Reliable decision support systems are also required to facilitate accurate prediction of herbage intake and animal responses to supplementation at pasture. With conserved forages there are opportunities to improve feed value by applying chemical or biological treatments to the harvested crop. These developments will undoubtedly contribute towards an increased reliance on forage in animal production systems in the next millennium.
