TI  - Leveraging Innovative Hybrid Machine Learning Models to Predict Drought and Optimize Water Resources Based on Climate Change
T2  - ADVANCES IN METEOROLOGY
LA  - English
KW  - drought prediction
KW  - ensemble methods
KW  - machine learning
KW  - water resource management
AB  - A major worldwide concern further compounded by climate change, population growth and expansion of cities, and unsustainable farming methods is water shortage. Drought prediction and the methods for using limited water are useful for reducing the negative effects on farming, environment, and people. This research presents a new meta-model that combines modified random forest (MRF), modified support vector machine (MSVM), and deep learning (DL) methods to increase the accuracy of drought prediction and, thereby, the effectiveness of water conservation. The RF component involves the use of performance-based weighting to trim down bias. SVM incorporates an adaptive cost function for imbalanced data. DL also involves to capture and infer temporal relationships. This integration is proposed to overcome the drawbacks of traditional machine learning (ML) algorithms and ensure the effectiveness across different data and climate settings. The proposed model was trained and tested on the DroughtED dataset, which includes over 3100 counties and multiple meteorological and hydrological features. The performance evaluation of the proposed approach in experimental studies confirms that the model is superior and reduces the prediction errors. The proposed model improves predictions for different drought severity levels. It achieves an average accuracy of 97.44% in mild drought, 98.66% in moderate drought, and 95.62% in severe drought. It performs better than the conventional approaches such as the standard SVM, LSTM, and RF. Furthermore, the error metrics, which include mean absolute error (MAE) and root mean square error (RMSE), have been reduced to 0.194 and 0.273, respectively. After the onset of drought is predicted, the water resource optimization component comes into play. This component is handled by proposing both linear programming (LP) and dynamic programming (DP) techniques to achieve efficient water allocations. The integration of predictive and optimization components creates an end-to-end decision support tool for sustainable water resource management.
