AB  - The Gnangara Sustainability Strategy-GSS is a cross-government initiative working on an action plan that will ensure the sustainable use of water for drinking and commercial purposes and to protect the environment in Western Australia. The Department of Water has joined forces with the Department of Agriculture and Food WA, Department of Environment and Conservation and Department for Planning and Infrastructure, Forest Products Commission, Water Corporation and CSIRO (forming taskforce group-TFG of the GSS project). The aim of the GSS is to make sure there is enough groundwater in the Gnangara Mound for drinking and commercial use, and to protect the environment-now and in the future.
   The combination of lower rainfall since 1975, land uses that affect recharge, and increased water extraction has resulted in falling groundwater levels in the Gnangara groundwater system near Perth, Western Australia. Groundwater currently supplies about 60% of the potable water supplies to the city of Perth (population 1.5 million) and more than 85% of all water demand (i. e. including irrigation of parks and gardens, industry and peri-urban horticulture). The Gnangara Mound is a large unconfined surface aquifer and in many locations the watertable is close to the surface. As a result, many significant environmental features, especially wetlands, are dependent on accessing the watertable for their existence. The rapid loss of Perth's surface water resources as a result of the decrease in rainfall resulted in groundwater being used more extensively. At the same time, pine plantations planted progressively over 23 km2 of the Mound since the 1960s were maturing and reduced recharge to zero, or negative amounts where tree roots accessed the watertable.
   A major challenge is to anticipate future water demands and supplies in a drying climate to accommodate the needs of Australia's most rapidly growing city as the urban area extends onto the recharge area of the unconfined aquifer. The management of the GGS is a major problem for water and environmental managers. The Gnangara groundwater system is very complex and interconnected system, posing significant challenges in managing its sustainably. Therefore, it is imperative that innovative modelling approaches are employed to assist in better decision making by modelling the feedback loops inherent in the system and to analyse the impact of alternative land use and water policy scenarios (recommended by the taskforce group at the local area level) in order to better understand the trade offs. These options include future land use changes, new water allocations, post pine land use options, establishing GDE requirements and bush burning regimes.
   This paper details a systems approach to developing an integrated decision support system (DSS) to enable these complex land and water use options to be evaluated in economic, social and environmental dimensions. A total of 29 sub-areas are modelled under six geographical zones. Each sub-area is modelled by the main interconnected six modules that lead to the quantitative indicators (environment, economic and social) values. The developed GSS-DSS is used by TFG to readily set up scenarios in the DSS and analyse their impacts on Gnangara groundwater system and its values. Preliminary results from the model/DSS are presented with an emphasis on understanding of the tradeoffs of changing climatic conditions and landuse planning; most scenarios lead to a declining water table in the GGS, which by 2030 is up to 8 meters lower from the current levels. Changing and reallocating landuse is able to improve recharge but this cannot reverse the overall trend of falling water levels as the climate signal is pervasive. It is anticipated that the DSS will play a critical role in developing the GSS and further enhance TFG understanding of the potential impacts of land use change and management on the mound.
